South Africa has achieved its current democratic status as a result of harsh political struggle which must be enforced at readily affordable costs. Social democracy came to be as a result of one-party democracy. As a result, certain decisions may not be taken if not by a 66 cent majority. In any democratic country, the common person has the right to freely speak his mind off and criticize any process in the government. These are rights and freedoms acquired since 1994. However, such practices are discouraged in recent events in the country.

A historic development that is more or less familiar to every single South African is the accessibility of health care facilities. Ninety percent of the country’s population has health insurance as opposed to only 65% five years ago. Moridality rates have drastically reduced enabling the country to be accorded a place in the top ten globally on the standard of health facilities. This seems to be a good turnout for a country which is home to atrocities either caused by the government or by the tokoloshe ruiners in the country. Stereotypical citizens in the Rainbow Nation always refer to otherpast events in the country amongst other events as the root of this notion. Polio which was a threat in the past is inconsequential in today’s South African statistics.
